                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ive run into several warriors, druids, and other players who roll on stuff because it pops up a window saying they can with Need Before Greed. Ive seen robes go to Leather classes, like Shamans, when there are Mages / Warlocks / Priests who couldve used, but that Shaman won when they just got a much better leather BP earlier. Ive watched Warriors roll on cloth shoulders. Ive seen Priests rolling on nice rogue daggers, and Mages rolling on one-handed slashers. Ive seen people begging for items in group for alternate characters, or ignoring their dying group to loot a chest or mine ore. Ive witnessed level 28 warriors be outperformed by a level 18 warrior simply because the level 18 paid attention. So Im starting a WoW Etiquette thread, and Ill start off with a few general statements:
<br />

<br />
If you cant find a group, join the LFG channel, or ask once or twice in general chat. Send tells to people. DO NOT SPAM. Spamming a question in chat channels will lead to being ignored by players, and in WoW it tells you, "X person has ignored you." We dont care if you are stuck finding the Mysterious Gauntlet of Uber. Look around first, dont spam the channel every 30 seconds bitching about how unfair it is you cant find the Gauntlet and its not right under yer nose! Also, if someone ignores you, generally its a good idea to stop bothering them. See aforementioned SPAM note. Likewise just because someone is doing the same quest as you, doesnt necessarily mean they HAVE to invite you to the group.
<br />

<br />
If you can wear leather, and you have cloth classes in the group, you have no business rolling on cloth. Same for mail / plate rolling on leather, and cloth users rolling on plate / mail / leather. In regards to weapons, just because you are trained for 1h as a mage, doesnt mean you need to roll on that uber purple Sword of Bitchslapping. Unless its stats are designed for all classes capable of wielding it, the item is best suited for people who WILL use it effectively such as warriors. Loot systems will vary from group to group and guild to guild, but people you need to use common sense when something drops. Enchanting is NOT an excuse to roll either. If something drops and you want it, donate for the item.
<br />

<br />
Anyone care to add?</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
